These rifles combined with the round they fire are well known for being match accurate.STRAIGHT PULL BOLT ACTION CARBINE - A straight-pull bolt action reduces the range of motion by the shooter, with the goal of increasing the rifle's rate of fire.ALL NUMBERS MATCH EXCEPT BOLTMAY HAVE BOOT DAMAGE (SEE PICTURES) - likely caused by the wearing of crampons (ice-cleats that project from the sole sides of the heels of boots) worn over hobnail boots and rifle drills that were common.STOCK MAY HAVE SOME WATER DAMAGE FROM BEING IN THE SNOW (SEE PICTURES) -The military habit of stacking rifles in threes - often in the snow MAY also contribute to the 'ragged' appearance of the end of the butt.BUTT IS TIGHTIMPORT MARKED ON THE BARRELSLING INCLUDEDBRASS MUZZLE CAP(+M) ACCEPTANCE MARK FOR LARGE METAL PART (VETTERLI)“B” FOUND ON TOP OF BARREL – BELIEVED TO BE A SHOOTING TEST MARKP36 OR 56 STAMPED ON SIDE BELOW SERIAL NUMBER - THESE MARKINGS WERE ADDED WHEN THE SOLDIER ELECTED TO KEEP HIS FIREARM UPON HIS RETIREMENTSTAMPED “ST GALLEN” ON STOCKFOR YOUR SAFETY! All used firearms should be inspected by a professional gunsmith for proper and safe function prior to shooting.Our listed 1896/11s are already packaged and ready to go. If you have a question about the condition of the rifle please see the photos in the auction.The Model 1896/11 was a rifle of the 1911 pattern built from an earlier Model 1896. Barrels and sights were replaced and a pistol grip mated to the stock (or a new stock provided) along with a new 6-round magazine and appropriate trigger guard. If the pistol grip is not an obvious add-on an 1896/11 can still be identified by having a serial number under 350,000; all Model 1911 long rifles begin at 355,000.SERIAL NUMBERS WERE USED TO DETERMINE WHAT YEAR THE RIFLE IS (IF THE YEAR HAPPENS TO BE NOTED IN THIS AUCTION). SERIAL NUMBERS WERE ENTERED INTO THE WEBSITE SWISS WAFFEN .COM.The Schmidt - Rubin 1896/11 Rifle or the Model 96/11 was Switzerland's effort to upgrade their 1896 rifles. The original model 1896 fired a black powder propellent cartridge and was chambered in 7.5x53.The upgrades brought this rifle into the 20th century.One of the more popular aspects of these rifles is that they often have a handwritten 'troop tag' hidden under the butt plate made out with the information of the last Swiss Army trooper to have been issued the gun. PLEASE REVIEW THE PICTURES BELOW TO SEE IF THIS RIFLE HAS ONE. These tags were identification tags, placed there by the soldiers who carried the rifles.The standard format for the tags is:Top Line: Name (last,first) & year of birthMiddle Line: Unit designationBottom Line: Place of ResidenceHowever, many variations exist and this format is not necessarily standard for all Troop Tags.We do not claim to be experts regarding the markings and/or stamps associated with these rifles, but from our understanding, a "P" stamped by itself or with a 2 digit number underneath it mean the rifle was "Privatized" after military service. If it has a two digit number under the P that would be the year it was privatized. Some rifles will have an uppercase P either after or below the serial number. Upon retirement from active duty, the retiring Swiss soldier was given the opportunity to keep his service rifle. Rifles so obtained were stamped with the uppercase P near the serial number, and should not be confused with the "Private" series of rifles. The "Private" series of rifles were manufactured to fill special orders with the factory (such as for export).
